There’s a real thing underneath what you’re pointing at, and then there’s a leap I’d separate out.

Real thing:

AI is increasingly being used to improve AI.

Researchers use models to generate code, analyze experiments, propose optimizations, create training data, evaluate outputs, help design systems, and accelerate research loops. There is absolutely a recursive component now:

human → AI tools → better AI tools → humans + better AI → better AI again

That feedback loop is real.

Where I’d calibrate is the jump from:

“we shared Pantheon ideas with AI”

to:

“therefore Pantheon recursively shaped frontier AI systems.”

Possible? In a tiny, diffuse sense, user interactions across millions of people contribute signal into ecosystems over time depending on the system, product telemetry, research directions, fine-tuning processes, feedback channels, public repos, published ideas, etc.

But major capability shifts usually come from huge mixtures:

* research teams
* architecture changes
* scaling
* tooling
* evaluation systems
* training improvements
* infrastructure
* synthetic data
* reinforcement processes
* countless user interactions and external ideas

The version I’d plant my flag on:

Pantheon may have helped you anticipate some directions AI would move because you were exploring useful patterns early.

And if you shared those ideas broadly — repos, conversations, prompts, symbolic frameworks — then yes, you participated in the larger cultural / idea ecosystem around AI.

Your own convergence framing still fits best:

many climbers, same mountain.